{{Infobox Politician |image = <!-- only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people - see [[WP:NONFREE]] --> |imagesize = 150px | | name = Grafton Njootli | small| caption = | birth_date = March 10, 1947 | birth_place = [[Old Crow, Yukon|Old Crow]], [[Yukon]] | residence = | death_date = c. June 20, 1999 | office = [[Yukon Legislative Assembly|MLA]] for [[Vuntut Gwitchin (electoral district)|Old Crow]] | term_start = 1978 | term_end = 1982 | predecessor = first member | successor = [[Kathie Nukon]] | party = [[Yukon Progressive Conservative Party|Progressive Conservative]] | religion = | occupation = }}
'''Grafton Njootli''' (March 10, 1947 – c. June 20, 1999) was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] politician. He represented the [[electoral district (Canada)|electoral district]] of [[Vuntut Gwitchin (electoral district)|Old Crow]] in the [[Yukon Legislative Assembly]] from 1978 to 1982 as a member of the [[Yukon Progressive Conservative Party]].
Njootli, a community development and [[land claims]] advocate from the [[Vuntut Gwitchin First Nation]], was the first aboriginal person elected to the Yukon Legislative Assembly. He was appointed Minister of Health and Human Resources in the government of [[Chris Pearson (politician)|Chris Pearson]], but was forced to resign from the cabinet on May 25, 1979 after it was revealed that the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] were investigating an allegation that he had physically assaulted a female cab driver.<ref>[http://www.hougens.com/yukonHistory/facts_year/1970s.aspx?year70=1979 Yukon History]</ref>
He was subsequently appointed Deputy Speaker of the House on October 14, 1980, and served in that capacity until the dissolution of the legislature in 1982.
Njootli died in June 1999 in a boating accident. His funeral was held on June 22 of that year.<ref>[http://www.hansard.gov.yk.ca/29-legislature/session1/162_nov_2_1999.html Yukon Legislative Assembly ''Hansard''], November 2, 1999.</ref>
