{{good article}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} {{Use Australian English|date=July 2013}} {{Infobox sportsperson | headercolor = green | textcolor = yellow | name = Sarah Vinci | image = Sarah Vinci 1.png | image_size = <!--Only for images narrower than 220 pixels. !--> | caption = No. 4 Sarah Vinci | birth_name = | fullname = | nickname = | nationality = {{AUS}} | residence = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1991|12|4|df=yes}} | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | height = <!-- {{convert| |cm}} (2012) !--> | weight = <!-- {{convert| |kg}} (2012) !--> | website = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} !--> | country = Australia | sport = Wheelchair basketball | event = Women's team | disability = [[Spina bifida]] | disability_class = [[1 point player|1.0]] | collegeteam = | club = Western Stars | team = | turnedpro = | coach = | retired = | coaching = | worlds = | regionals = | nationals = | olympics = | paralympics = | highestranking = | pb = | medaltemplates= {{MedalSport |Wheelchair basketball}} {{MedalCompetition|[[Paralympic Games]]}} {{MedalSilver|[[2012 Summer Paralympics|2012 London]]|[[Wheelchair basketball at the 2012 Summer Paralympics|Women's Wheelchair basketball]]}} {{MedalCompetition|U25 Women's World Championships}} {{MedalSilver|[[2011 Women's U25 Wheelchair Basketball World Championship|2011 St Catharines]]|Women's wheelchair basketball}} {{MedalSilver|[[2015 Women's U25 Wheelchair Basketball World Championship|2015 Beijing]]|Women's wheelchair basketball}} }}
'''Sarah Vinci''' (born 4 December 1991) is a [[1 point player|1 point]] [[wheelchair basketball]] player who plays for the Perth Western Stars in the Australian Women's National Wheelchair Basketball League. She made her debut with the [[Australia women's national wheelchair basketball team]], known as the Gliders, in 2011, when she played in the Osaka Cup in Japan. Vinci represented [[Australia at the 2012 Summer Paralympics|Australia]] at the [[2012 Summer Paralympics]] in London in wheelchair basketball, winning a silver medal. Her most recent international appearance was at the 2013 Osaka Cup.
==Personal== Vinci was born on 4 December 1991 in [[Perth, Western Australia]].<ref name=bbaus>{{cite web|url=http://gawain.sportingpulse.com/nfnn/team_info.cgi?action=PSTATS&client=1-6734-84473-163738-10141848&pID=189767466&pname=Sarah%20Vinci&news_task=DETAIL |title=Player statistics for Sarah Vinci&nbsp;— SportingPulse |publisher=Gawain.sportingpulse.com |date= |accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=aussiemedia>{{cite book|title=Media Guide, London 2012 Paralympic Games|publisher=Australian Paralympic Committee|year=2012|location=Homebush Bay, New South Wales|chapter=Wheelchair Basketball|pages=92–99 [99]}}</ref> She has [[spina bifida]].<ref name=aussiemedia/><ref name=apc/> {{As of|2013}}, Vinci lives in [[Spearwood, Western Australia]],<ref name=aussiemedia/><ref name=apc/><ref name=fromfa>{{cite web|last=Robinson |first=Chris |url=http://www.perthnow.com.au/sport/2022-world-cup-bid/seven-wa-basketballers-picked-for-paralympics/story-e6frg25u-1226418182721 |title=Seven WA basketballers picked for Paralympics |publisher=Perth Now |date=5 July 2012 |accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> and is a student. She has already attended a [[Technical and Further Education]] (TAFE) institute, where she earned a [[academic certificate|certificate]] in [[digital media]].<ref name=bbaus/><ref name=apc/>
==Career== [[File:040912 - Sarah Vinci - 3b - 2012 Summer Paralympics (01).jpg|thumb|left|Vinci at the 2012 London Paralympics]] [[File:040912 - Sarah Vinci - 3b - 2012 Summer Paralympics (03).JPG|thumb|right|Vinci at the 2012 London Paralympics]] [[File:The interview with four players.ogg|thumb|right|[[:n:Main Page|Wikinews reporters]] interview Australian Glider Leanne Del Toso, Sarah Vinci, Amber Merritt and Clare Nott|left]] Vinci is a [[1 point player|1 point]] [[wheelchair basketball]] player. She started playing wheelchair basketball in 2006.<ref name=apc>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org.au/team/sarah-vinci |title=Sarah Vinci |publisher=Australian Paralympic Committee |location=Australia |year=2012 |accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=aussprtcom>{{cite web|url=https://ausport.gov.au/supporting/funding/grants_and_scholarships/grant_funding_report|title=Grant Funding Report|publisher=Australian Sports Commission|location=Bruce, Australian Capital Territory|accessdate=15 September 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120410184601/http://www.ausport.gov.au/supporting/funding/grants_and_scholarships/grant_funding_report|archivedate=10 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Vinci joined the Perth Western Stars in the [[Women's National Wheelchair Basketball League]] (WNWBL) in 2009,<ref name=perthwesternstars>{{cite web|url=http://www.basketballvictoria.com.au/index.php?id=138 |title=Gliders v Japan |publisher=Basketball Victoria |date= |accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref> and has been with the club into the 2013 season.<ref name=apc/> In 2010, she won the league's junior championship, the [[Kevin Coombs]] Cup, when her team beat the New South Wales side 63–58.<ref name=apc/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.basketball.net.au/index.php?id=845 |title=Wheelchair Basketball |publisher=[[Basketball Australia]] |accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref>
Vinci was selected to participate in a national team training camp in 2010,<ref name=selected2010>{{cite news|accessdate=18 September 2012|page=77|title=Local Gliders|newspaper=Hills Shire Times|location=Sydney, Australia|date=19 January 2010|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AUNB:ACGB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12D9D9BB45751458&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=1053B823C33F21F9}}</ref> and made her debut with the national team, universally known as the Gliders,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.basketball.net.au/index.php?id=334 |title=Gliders |publisher=[[Basketball Australia]] |accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref> the following year, when she played in the Osaka Cup in Japan.<ref name=apc/> She competed in the 2011 Asia Oceania Regional Championships,<ref name=southokorea>{{cite news|url=http://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/sport/a/-/basketball/10501153/wheelcats-stars-headline-national-teams/ |title=Wheelcats, Stars headline national teams |newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |date=19 October 2011 |accessdate=27 July 2012}}</ref> the 2011 U25 World Championships,<ref name=apc/><ref name=yeppersthere>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?client=1-6734-0-0-0&sID=119018&&news_task=DETAIL&articleID=16301816 |title=Aust U25 Women’s Wheelchair team depart for Canada&nbsp;— Women’s National Wheelchair Basketball League |publisher=SportingPulse |date=30 June 2012 |accessdate=28 July 2012}}</ref> and the 2012 BT Paralympic World Cup, competing in the final match against Germany.<ref name=btgetty>{{cite web|url=http://www.zimbio.com/photos/Sarah+Vinci/BT+Paralympic+World+Cup+Day+Three/fNFbI4UhJIY |title=Sarah Vinci photos - BT Paralympic World Cup - Day Five|publisher=Zimbio Entertainment |date=26 May 2012 |accessdate=22 July 2013}}</ref>
Vinci was selected to represent [[Australia at the 2012 Summer Paralympics|Australia]] at the [[2012 Summer Paralympics]] in wheelchair basketball.<ref name=snamedteam>{{cite web |url=http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=8494652 |title=Games wheelchair basketball squads named |publisher=Nine MSN |location=Australia |date= |accessdate=13 July 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150614234319/http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=8494652 |archivedate=14 June 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=playined2012wa>{{cite web|last=Foreman |first=Glen |url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/london-olympics/brad-ness-ready-to-compete-in-fourth-paralympics/story-fndpu6dv-1226419892151 |title=Brad Ness ready to compete in fourth Paralympics |publisher=News.com.au |date=8 July 2012 |accessdate=27 July 2012}}</ref> The London Games were her first.<ref name=firstgames>{{cite news |url=http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=8494652 |title=Games wheelchair Basketball Squads Named |newspaper=Nine MSN |accessdate=27 July 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150614234319/http://wwos.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=8494652 |archivedate=14 June 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She attended a Paralympic farewell ceremony at Perth's State Basketball Centre in late July.<ref name=heraldsundislike>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/london-olympics/aussie-paralympians-throw-down-gauntlet-to-the-poms/story-fn9dheyx-1226434175730|newspaper=Herald Sun|accessdate=27 July 2012|title=Aussie paralympians throw down gauntlet to the Poms |date=24 July 2012|first=Glen|last=Foreman }}</ref>
In the group stage, the [[Australia women's national wheelchair basketball team at the 2012 Summer Paralympics]] posted wins against Brazil,<ref name="Gliders Prevail in Thriller">{{cite web|url=http://london2012.paralympic.org.au/news/gliders-prevail-thriller |title=Gliders Prevail in Thriller |date=30 August 2012 |publisher=[[Australian Paralympic Committee]] |last=Abbott |first=Chris |accessdate=1 February 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120903104118/http://london2012.paralympic.org.au/news/gliders-prevail-thriller |archivedate= 3 September 2012 |df= }}</ref> Great Britain,<ref name="Gliders Win Comfortably Against Host">{{cite web|url=http://london2012.paralympic.org.au/news/gliders-win-comfortably-against-host |title=Gliders Win Comfortably Against Host |date=31 August 2012 |publisher=[[Australian Paralympic Committee]] |last=Abbott |first=Chris |accessdate=1 February 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902103742/http://london2012.paralympic.org.au/news/gliders-win-comfortably-against-host |archivedate= 2 September 2012 |df= }}</ref> and the Netherlands,<ref name="Gliders Secure Quarter Final Place">{{cite web|url=http://london2012.paralympic.org.au/news/gliders-secure-quarter-final-place |title=Gliders Secure Quarter Final Place |date=2 September 2012 |publisher=[[Australian Paralympic Committee]] |last=Abbott |first=Chris |accessdate=1 February 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120909172934/http://london2012.paralympic.org.au/news/gliders-secure-quarter-final-place |archivedate= 9 September 2012 |df= }}</ref> but lost to Canada.<ref name="Gliders shocked by Canada">{{cite web |url=http://www.basketball.net.au/index.php?id=302&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=2701&cHash=a1295ff31f |title=Gliders shocked by Canada |date=2 September 2012 |publisher=[[Basketball Australia]] |accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref> This was enough to advance the Gliders to the quarter-finals, where they beat Mexico.<ref name="Gliders Dominate Mexico">{{cite web|url=http://london2012.paralympic.org.au/news/gliders-dominate-mexico |title=Gliders Dominate Mexico |last=Abbott |first=Chris |date=4 September 2012 |publisher=[[Australian Paralympic Committee]] |accessdate=2 February 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905004501/http://london2012.paralympic.org.au/news/gliders-dominate-mexico |archivedate= 5 September 2012 |df= }}</ref> The Gliders then defeated the United States by a point to set up a final clash with Germany.<ref name="semi final abc">{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-09-07/gliders-down-champions-to-reach-final/4247772 |title=Gliders down champions to reach final |newspaper=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=7 September 2012 |accessdate=30 January 2013 }}</ref> The Gliders lost 44–58, and earned a silver medal.<ref name="Gliders get rolled">{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/sport/basketball/gliders-get-rolled-for-gold-by-german-muscle-20120908-25kzz.html#ixzz2JZwF7Ntf |title=Gliders get rolled for gold by German muscle |newspaper=[[The Age]] |last=Paxinos|first=Stathi |date=9 September 2013 |accessdate=1 February 2013}}</ref>
At the 2013 Osaka Cup in Japan,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.basketball.net.au/fileadmin/user_upload/_temp_/2013_Gliders_Osaka_Cup_Player_Profiles_Feb_01.pdf |title=2013 Osaka Cup, Japan, Australian Gliders Player Profiles |publisher=[[Basketball Australia]] |accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref> Vinci and the Gliders successfully defended the title they had previously won in 2008, 2009, 2010 and 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.basketball.net.au/index.php?id=302&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=2806&cHash=156fce3191 |title=Aussie Gliders 2013 Osaka Cup Champions |date=17 February 2013 |publisher=[[Basketball Australia]] |accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref>
